Now memorials are uninter- rupted, and exact relations of things, but naked and without any ornament of figures. Whence Cicero, in book v. of his Familiar Epistles, in a very elegant epistle to the famous historian, L. Lucceius Quintus’s son, saith that he will make a memorial of the transactions in his consulship, to the end that Lucceius might compose a history of them.
